function minCost(sentence, k) {
    const words = sentence.split(' ');
    const dp = new Array(words.length + 1).fill(Infinity);
    dp[0] = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < words.length; ++i) {
        let length = 0;
        for (let j = i; j >= 0; --j) {
            length += words[j].length;
            if (length + (i - j) <= k) {
                dp[i + 1] = Math.min(dp[i + 1], dp[j] + (k - length - (i - j)) * (k - length - (i - j)));
            } else {
                break;
            }
            length += 1;
        }
    }
    return dp[dp.length - 1];
}
```


    1. Split `sentence` into words separated by spaces.
2. Initialize the dynamic programming table `dp` to store the minimum total cost of splitting the `i` first words. `dp[0] = 0`.
3. For each word with index `i` in the smaller string, calculate the cost for putting it in a single row with some of the previous words. This is done by iterating backwards through the words from `i`, joining consecutive words one at a time until the row length is greater than `k`.
4. If the row length is less or equal to `k`, calculate the row cost for this combination of words and update `dp[i + 1] = min(dp[i + 1], dp[j] + cost)`. Otherwise, break the inner loop since adding more words will only make the row length even larger.
5. Return the last value in `dp`, which represents the minimum total cost for splitting the entire sentence into rows.

